- They try to separate you from the group of people you’re with
- They will forcefully try to keep you away from anyone else by threatening harm on the person. 
- If you ask to speak with the loved one, they will threaten to hurt them. 
- They prefer payment methods of Cash App/PayPal/Venmo for instant transfer. 
- They want you to send money through friends and family instead of as a good/service as it’s much harder to dispute. 
- They will ask for more money to try to fully capitalize on the situation. 
- If you find yourself in this situation, you may want to: get someone to contact this person (through social media or cell phone) to confirm their whereabouts; delay the situation without upsetting - they’re in control, but the more time you take, the more time you have to find out the validity of the situation; get someone else to contact your local authorities; the mute button is your friend.

node.text:
Just call me - TheNomadicTeacher.

9 years later, I’ve made it back home! Officially back at my Alma mater, but this time as an employee. I received an incredible opportunity to teach at The University of Memphis - Campus School. I student taught at this school and have always dreamed of becoming a teacher here. Along with the move, I will also be in a new grade level. Any guesses what grade I will be teaching?

node.text:
One thing I can appreciate during this era of learning is all the new technology.
Last week we played around with the free app JigSpace. It allows you to explore and share interactive 3D knowledge. If you have an iPad or iPhone, download the app to see all the augmented realities you and your students can discover. It also gives you the ability to create your own which I’m going to try this week - I’ll keep y’all updated!

node.text:
This week on teaching during a pandemic ... we resort to potato filters as a form of engagement.

During the last two weeks, I went from teaching traditionally to teaching from home because of a Covid exposure. One class is still at school while the other is online.

On Monday, I’ll be cleared to return to school and teach one class while the other stays virtual. 

What is your current teaching situation?

Thanks to the @ScholasticBookshelf, my class is still making time for #reading despite my teaching math and science this year! Aside from content reading, I am still able to read aloud to my homeroom every single day. No matter the subject area we teach, reading should be at the forefront. Currently we are reading, Percy Jackson - The Lightning Thief. To bring alive the magic in this book, we used the bookshelf to find A Magical Summer of Reading, which has an interview with the author, Rick Riordan. My students loved learning about the inspiration behind the main character and how life events can inspire their writing. Maybe one of them will become a writer one day!

Scholastic has a history of sharing great stories, with parents, teachers & kids as they celebrate turning 100 this month! To find great stories to discuss topics with your students, check out the @ScholasticBookshelf to #ReadOn #Scholastic100 #ScholasticPartner

node.text: Fear is real. We are allowed to be scared, but we can’t stay scared. With the @ScholasticBookshelf, I’m helping to answer the question, “How do we move forward?” I scrolled the Bookshelf to find Amulet, the perfect story that helps us talk about #courage, and today our morning meeting was centered around the topic. In this two-part morning meeting, we discussed how we get through challenging times and looked at how the author of Amulet uses illustrations to depict character's emotions throughout the book.
